I don&#39;t know if this helps or if read the thread correctly, but could he
setup a ant property with his default value and if he wants to override it
just pass in the new
value on the command line.  I use this method to substitute different
properties/config files for the server that I am building.  So &quot;ant all&quot;
will build and test on my development box where as &quot;ant all -Dserver=test&quot;
will build and test on my test server. &quot;server&quot; corresponds to a section of
the path where the config files are stored. So to utilize the property I
have the following in my ant script.

     &lt;copy todir = &quot;${app.build.home}/WEB-INF&quot;&gt;
        &lt;fileset dir=&quot;${source.home}/WEB-INF/${server}&quot;&gt;
           &lt;include name = &quot;**/web.xml&quot;/&gt;
        &lt;/fileset&gt;
     &lt;/copy&gt;

This really does not require any &quot;if&quot; logic as a value set in the command
line overrides any internally set properties.  This technique is explained
in &quot;Ant The Definitive Guide&quot; by Tilly & Burke page 256 Appendix B Ant
Solutions.

